<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="431" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,541,1537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,541,566]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from other congeners by the somewhat (posteriorly) ovoid body, grayish brown basic coloration, small eyes, short, blunt-tipped median projection on frons, and noticeable skull-like markings on the hemelytron (Fig. 
<number box="[346,357,613,637]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431" value="1.0">1</number>
B, circled image).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="431" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,541,1537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,649,674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">Description.</emphasis>
Body generally grayish brown, somewhat ovoid; dorsal surface mat or shagreened, with sparsely distributed, long, silky, erect setae and short, reclining, woolly setae. Head whitish, with irregular sanguineous stripes laterally; frons with a short, thumb-like, blunt-tipped median projection; eye small; vertex wide. Antenna grayish brown, partly tinged with red; segment I coffee brown. Labium shiny dark brown, long, extending beyond apex of metacoxa, reaching abdominal sternum VI or VII. Pronotum with white basal margin; collar area with sanguineous spots; mesoscutum with four tooth-like, dark markings; scutellum arched mesially, with pale apex; pleura dark brown, rather shiny; episternum tinged with red; ostiolar peritreme creamy yellow. Hemelytron irregularly speckled, with a set of four dark, skull-like markings on clavus and corium (Fig. 
<number box="[1207,1217,901,925]" pageId="2" pageNumber="431" value="1.0">1</number>
A–B); cuneus dark brown, rather strongly deflected at cuneal fracture; membrane dark smoky brown. Coxae and legs dark brown, except for pale metacoxa, all tibiae and tarsi brown. Abdomen unicolorously dark brown. 
<emphasis box="[1164,1329,973,997]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation captionStart-0="FIGURE 4" captionStart-1="FIGURE 5" captionStart-2="FIGURE 6" captionStartId-0="8.[151,250,1932,1955]" captionStartId-1="9.[151,250,1754,1777]" captionStartId-2="10.[151,250,2014,2037]" captionTargetBox-0="[196,1401,614,1882]" captionTargetBox-1="[190,1378,212,1712]" captionTargetBox-2="[174,1392,603,1986]" captionTargetId-0="figure@8.[151,1436,591,1911]" captionTargetId-1="figure@9.[151,1436,177,1733]" captionTargetId-2="figure@10.[153,1438,575,2027]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionTargetPageId-2="10" captionText-0="FIGURE 4. Male genital segment (pygophore) and phallotheca of Thai hallodapines named on the figure. Scale bars 0.2 mm." captionText-1="FIGURE 5. Male genitalia (left paramere and endosoma) of Thai hallodapines named on the figure. Scale bars 0.1 mm." captionText-2="FIGURE 6. Images of endosoma of Thai hallodapines named on the figure." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/224238/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/224239/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/224240/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="431">
Figs. 
<number pageId="2" pageNumber="431" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4– 6</number>
</figureCitation>
